Now, unlike dp[i][j] we have-->

dp[i][target]

means

Can I make target using elements from index 0...i?

This definition is EVERYTHING.

Decision

At every index,

Suppose

arr = [2,5,7]

i = 1

arr[i] = 5

You only have two choices.

Don't take it
Target remains same.

Example

Target = 7

Ignore 5

Need 7 from previous elements.
Take it

Only if

arr[i] <= target

Then

Target = 7

Take 5

Need 2 from previous elements.

See?

The target decreases.
Transition

This is the most important recurrence in subsequence DP.

bool notTake = dp[i-1][target];

bool take = false;

if(arr[i] <= target)
    take = dp[i-1][target-arr[i]];

dp[i][target] = take || notTake;

Base Cases

These are very important.

Base 1

If

target == 0

return

true

Why?

Because we can always choose no elements.

The empty subset has sum 0.

So in tabulation,

for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    dp[i][0] = true;
Base 2

First element.

If

arr[0] == target

then

dp[0][arr[0]] = true;

because using only the first element,

we can form exactly its value.

class Solution {
public:

    bool isSubsetSum(vector<int>& arr, int target)
    {
        int n = arr.size();

        vector<bool> prev(target+1,false);

        prev[0] = true;

        if(arr[0] <= target)
            prev[arr[0]] = true;

        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++)
        {
            vector<bool> curr(target+1,false);

            curr[0] = true;

            for(int t = 1; t <= target; t++)
            {
                bool notTake = prev[t];

                bool take = false;

                if(arr[i] <= t)
                    take = prev[t-arr[i]];

                curr[t] = take || notTake;
            }

            prev = curr;
        }

        return prev[target];
    }
};
